    <div class="hero-insight">
      <div class="hero-stat">For every 13% increase in Bitcoin's age, <em>the trend price doubles.</em></div>
      <p class="hero-body">This relationship &mdash; <em>proportional</em><sup title="The characterization of Bitcoin's power law growth as 'proportional and sustainable' originates from Matthew Mežinskis (Porkopolis Economics).">1</sup>, not exponential &mdash; has held across 15 years and nine orders of magnitude, from $0.01 to $100,000. It describes growth that naturally decelerates as the network matures: fast enough to be transformative, slow enough to be <em>sustainable</em>.<sup title="The characterization of Bitcoin's power law growth as 'proportional and sustainable' originates from Matthew Mežinskis (Porkopolis Economics).">1</sup> It is not an investment thesis. It is an empirical observation about how Bitcoin scales.</p>
      <p class="hero-body">The model is called the <strong>Power Law</strong>. Its R&sup2; exceeds 95%.<sup title="R² (R-squared) measures how well a statistical model fits observed data. A value of 1.0 means the model explains 100% of the variation; 0 means none. An R² above 0.95 is exceptionally rare for any financial model and indicates the Power Law explains more than 95% of Bitcoin's long-term price variation.">2</sup> Its structural floor &mdash; the boundary below which Bitcoin has never sustained a daily close &mdash; has survived every major stress test of the last decade, including the March 2020 COVID crash and the 2022 FTX collapse. And it has held not only in-sample but out-of-sample: first identified in 2014, every subsequent year has confirmed the trajectory.</p>
    </div>

