    <!-- THE 13% INSIGHT -->
    <div class="section">
      <h2>What &ldquo;Proportional Growth&rdquo; Means</h2>
      <p class="prose">In exponential models, the price doubles at a fixed calendar interval &mdash; every four years, regardless of how old the system is. This is mathematically unsustainable: it demands the same absolute performance forever, eventually requiring infinite growth in finite time.</p>
      <p class="prose">In a power law, the doubling time <em>stretches</em>. It requires a constant percentage of the network's existing age &mdash; roughly 13% &mdash; not a fixed number of years. This means each successive doubling takes longer in calendar time, even though the proportional relationship stays constant.</p>
      <div class="insight-box">
        <p>When Bitcoin was 1,000 days old, it needed 128 more days to double its fair value. At 5,000 days old, it needs 638 more days. At 6,000 days: 766 more days. The growth continues, but the pace naturally decelerates &mdash; which is what makes it sustainable.</p>
      </div>
      <p class="prose">This is why the conventional metric of CAGR (Compound Annual Growth Rate) can be misleading when applied to Bitcoin. CAGR assumes constant percentage growth per year &mdash; exponential by definition. Bitcoin's growth is better described as <em>proportional</em>: it scales as a constant proportion of its own age, producing a trajectory that is robust precisely because it doesn't demand ever-increasing performance.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- S2F COMPARISON -->

    <!-- DECLINING CAGR vs S&P 500 -->
    <div class="section">
      <h2>How Bitcoin's Growth Rate Compares</h2>
      <p class="prose">Because Bitcoin follows a power law, its annualized growth rate naturally declines over time. But even as it decelerates, the projected returns remain substantially higher than traditional equity markets for decades. The table below shows the Power Law's implied CAGR (Compound Annual Growth Rate) from each starting year to 2035, compared to the S&amp;P 500's historical average of roughly 10% per year.<sup title="This comparison of declining Bitcoin CAGR against traditional equity returns is inspired by analysis from Matthew Mežinskis (Porkopolis Economics).">4</sup></p>
      <div class="chart-container">
        <div class="chart-title">Power Law Implied CAGR vs. S&amp;P 500</div>
        <div class="chart-subtitle">Projected annualized return from each year to 2035, using trend (fair value) line</div>
        <div class="chart-wrapper" style="height:320px"><canvas id="cagrChart"></canvas></div>
        <div class="chart-source">CAGR calculated from Power Law trend values. S&amp;P 500 historical average ~10% annualized (nominal). Bitcoin's CAGR declines because the Power Law describes proportional, not exponential, growth &mdash; but remains above equity-market averages for decades.</div>
      </div>
      <p class="prose">The key insight: even the <em>decelerating</em> version of Bitcoin's growth outperforms the historical average of the world's most successful equity index. This isn't a prediction &mdash; it's what the model's trajectory implies if the 15-year pattern continues. The growth slows, but the slowed growth is still extraordinary by any traditional benchmark.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="compare-box">
      <h3>How the Power Law Differs from Stock-to-Flow</h3>
      <div class="compare-grid">
        <div class="compare-col stf">
          <h4>Stock-to-Flow (S2F)<sup title="The Stock-to-Flow model, created by pseudonymous analyst PlanB in 2019, became one of the most widely followed Bitcoin price models during the 2020–2021 bull market. It predicted Bitcoin would reach $100K–$288K by late 2021 based on the post-halving supply reduction. When the price peaked at ~$69K and subsequently fell to ~$16K, the model's predictions were off by 50–80%, leading to widespread criticism and abandonment by many of its former advocates.">3</sup></h4>
          <p>Driven by <strong>scarcity</strong> &mdash; models price as a function of supply halvings. Gained wide popularity during 2020&ndash;2021 but predicts exponential growth that must accelerate forever. Failed to predict the 2021&ndash;2022 cycle, missing targets by 50&ndash;80%. Implies Bitcoin is valuable because it is <em>rare</em>.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="compare-col pl">
          <h4>The Power Law</h4>
          <p>Driven by <strong>adoption</strong> &mdash; models price as a function of network growth over time. Predicts proportional growth that naturally decelerates. Has maintained its predicted range for 15+ years across nine orders of magnitude. Implies Bitcoin is valuable because it is a <em>growing, useful network</em>.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

