    <div class="section">
      <h2>A System, Not an Asset</h2>
      <p class="prose">Power laws don't describe assets. They describe <em>systems</em> &mdash; complex, self-organizing structures whose growth is governed by internal feedback dynamics rather than external market sentiment. Stocks fluctuate with earnings and psychology. Commodities respond to supply and demand. But systems &mdash; cities, organisms, networks &mdash; scale according to structural rules that produce predictable mathematical relationships across many orders of magnitude.</p>
      <p class="prose">The fact that Bitcoin follows a power law is evidence of what it actually is: not an asset to be traded, but a <em>system</em> to be understood. Its growth is <em>proportional</em><sup>1</sup> &mdash; scaling as a constant fraction of its own age &mdash; and <em>sustainable</em><sup>1</sup> &mdash; decelerating naturally as the network matures. This same proportional, sustainable pattern appears across biology, urban science, and network theory. Understanding the precedents makes Bitcoin's trajectory structurally expected rather than surprising.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- ── KLEIBER'S LAW ── -->
    <div class="section">
      <h3>Kleiber's Law: How Life Scales</h3>
      <p class="prose">In 1932, biologist Max Kleiber discovered that metabolic rate across mammals scales with body mass raised to the power of 0.75. A mouse burns far more energy per gram than an elephant. This isn't a coincidence &mdash; it's a structural law that emerges from the <em>branching architecture</em> of biological distribution networks: circulatory systems, respiratory trees, and neural pathways all follow the same fractal branching geometry, and that geometry produces power law scaling.</p>
      <div class="chart-container">
        <div class="chart-title">Kleiber's Law: Metabolic Rate vs. Body Mass</div>
        <div class="chart-subtitle">Log-log scale &middot; Representative mammalian species &middot; Exponent &asymp; 0.75</div>
        <div class="chart-wrapper" style="height:280px"><canvas id="kleiberChart"></canvas></div>
        <div class="chart-source">Data representative of Kleiber's observations. On a log-log scale, every species falls on the same straight line &mdash; the visual signature of a power law. The same straight line appears in Bitcoin's price history.</div>
      </div>
      <p class="prose">The key insight isn't just that the relationship exists &mdash; it's that it's <em>proportional and sustainable</em>. Larger mammals don't need exponentially more energy; they achieve greater efficiency through structural scaling. The growth is governed by physics, not by intention. Bitcoin's hash rate scales with price following an analogous relationship &mdash; security increasing predictably with value, governed by the same mathematics that governs how elephants breathe.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- ── BRANCHING NETWORKS ── -->
    <div class="section">
      <h3>Branching Networks: Nature's Distribution System</h3>
      <p class="prose">The reason Kleiber's Law works is that biological organisms distribute resources through <em>branching fractal networks</em> &mdash; the same self-similar pattern that appears in river deltas, tree root systems, lightning bolts, and the bronchial passages of lungs. These networks follow a universal scaling principle: each level of branching divides into a predictable number of sub-branches, with the diameter and flow rate at each level following a power law.</p>

