        <div class="chart-source">The same fractal branching geometry appears in river systems, biological vasculature, and network topologies. Each produces power law scaling because the branching structure distributes resources according to the same mathematical rules, regardless of the medium.</div>
      </div>
      <p class="prose">This is the deep structural insight: power laws aren't coincidences that happen to appear in unrelated domains. They emerge from a <em>universal architecture</em> &mdash; branching distribution networks that optimize the transport of resources (blood, water, information, value) across a system. Geoffrey West's work at the Santa Fe Institute showed that this branching geometry is the common root of Kleiber's Law, urban scaling, and network growth. Bitcoin's transaction and mining networks follow the same branching topology, which is why the same mathematical form appears.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- ── CITY SCALING with dual visual ── -->
    <div class="section">
      <h3>City Scaling: Geoffrey West's 15% Rule</h3>
      <p class="prose">Physicist Geoffrey West and colleagues discovered that cities exhibit a remarkable dual scaling pattern. Physical infrastructure scales <em>sublinearly</em> (exponent ~0.85) &mdash; a city twice as large needs only 85% more roads and pipes, not twice as many. But socioeconomic outputs &mdash; GDP, patents, wages, innovation &mdash; scale <em>superlinearly</em> (exponent ~1.15). Every new person added creates more potential connections, driving disproportionate productivity.</p>

